I'm deciding to play Queen's Gambit - my second favorite opening overall (first being Sicilian of course! (duh))
I'm deciding to play Queen's Gambit - my second favorite opening overall (first being Sicilian of course! (duh))
Wow! Esthetically speaking, this just looks so cool! I didn't even know what the opening was called back then. Now that I look it up, I learn that it is called Austrian defence.

Here, the database shows cxd5 as the most popular move. Maybe because after Qxd5, white plays Nf3 and is ahead in developing minor pieces. Or the game can also progress like this - 3)cxd5 Qxd5 4) Nc3! Qxd4 5)Qxd4 cxd4 Nb5! - I think this variation is dynamic and very good for white. But regardless, I chose to play Nf3 because I didn't want to mess up the four pawn structure on the left side of the board. It's something like a deadlock between soldiers before the commence of a HUGE battle!
did I say a deadlock?! The black queen pounces right in to attack my king

Here I also had Bd2, but I think Nc3 makes more of a statement in saying that "You shall not pass" (sorry had to quote Gandalf here :P ). Bd2 is decent but two knights standing guard to your fortress just has some kickassness to it :P.
Black wants to open up the bishop diagonal and break white's pawn structure by doing cxd4
Here, I just make a threat for black's queen. If my knight moves, the bishop will be ready to snipe the queen. It's best for the black queen to retreat from my black bishop's "line of fire".
Going to avenge the fallen soldier on c4!
Going to avenge the fallen soldier on c4!
I don't know about the placement of bishop here. Black could have tried to hit the white wall by doing cxd4 or something
"Revenge is the sweetest thing next to getting..." (sorry had to quote Tupac - Hail Mary here! :P)..but my pieces look awesomely (<-- wow that's a word) positioned right now.
White should develop some more artillery before trying to invade the white camp at this point. A bishop and both knights are still sitting at home squares.
Fancier than exd4! :P
